<note><title>Best Practices -- [Introduction 4]</title><content><![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd">

<en-note><div><ul><li><div>develop your mod on the Beta Branch so you can stay ahead of the curve and be compatible with the main branch as soon as that next update is pushed live</div></li><li><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">comment</span> your code... like, <span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">lots</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">use version control like Git!</span></div></li><ul><li><div>use <a href="https://nvie.com/posts/a-successful-git-branching-model/?">Vincent Driessen&apos;s <span style="font-style: italic;">A successful Git branching model</span></a>&nbsp;to ensure a clean working environment and clear version history</div></li></ul><li><div>keep track of how much time you&apos;ve spent developing your mod. this is very rewarding, and gives you some insight into your behaviour as a person when coding</div></li><li><div>test frequently, and thoroughly</div></li><li><div>test with friends</div></li><li><div>send to friends for them to test on their own</div></li><li><div>keep an eye on your steam profile; if you get a comment on one of your mods regarding a bug someone found, you&apos;d best address it so people know you&apos;ve got them covered. an informed community following is a happier following!</div></li><li><div>keep doing it for fun!!! as soon as you start to lose sight of why you&apos;re making mods, it&apos;s a sign something&apos;s gone wrong.</div></li></ul><div><br/></div></div><div><br/></div></en-note>]]></content><created>20200212T172515Z</created><updated>20200212T210617Z</updated><note-attributes><author>Shrooblord</author><source>desktop.win</source><source-application>evernote.win32</source-application></note-attributes></note></en-export>
